        "content": "<p>Is there a theorem in Mathlib that says eventual domination is a well-ordering?</p>",
        "id": 529905764,
        "sender_full_name": "Janitha Aswedige",
        "timestamp": 1753108861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it is my understanding that well-orderings are total (linear) orders, meaning eventual domination is not a well-order?</p>",
        "id": 529907759,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1753109459
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>since you can take functions like <code>fun x =&gt; if Even n then 1 else 0</code> and <code>fun x =&gt; if Odd n then 1 else 0</code>, which aren't comparable?</p>",
        "id": 529908125,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1753109577
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and even then, i'm pretty sure this relation is not well-founded... since the element <code>fun x =&gt; 2</code> has infinitely many functions which it dominates, i.e. pick one from <code>fun x =&gt; if x &gt; n then 1 else 0</code></p>",
        "id": 529908610,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1753109724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>indeed it is a strict partial order but not well-founded as it allows for infinite descending chains</p>",
        "id": 529908682,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Cipollina",
        "timestamp": 1753109744
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yea, so by both marks it is not a well-order</p>",
        "id": 529908769,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1753109777
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed. I made a mistake. Sorry. I’m working in a special set of functions on natural numbers that contains the constant function 1, and the identity function, and which is closed under addition, multiplication, and exponentiation. Eventual domination is a well-ordering on it.</p>",
        "id": 529910020,
        "sender_full_name": "Janitha Aswedige",
        "timestamp": 1753110123
    },
